<DOC><DOCNO> AP890124-0074 </DOCNO><FILEID>AP-NR-01-24-89 1054EST</FILEID><FIRST>r i PM-Benin     01-24 0212</FIRST><SECOND>PM-Benin,0219</SECOND><HEAD>West African President Orders Troops To Shoot Rioters On Sight</HEAD><DATELINE>COTONOU, Benin (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   President Mathieu Kerekou ordered troops toopen fire on crowds following anti-government riots in the capital,official reports said today.   State radio broadcast Kerekou's order for soldiers ``to shootwithout warning on any group that forms and this throughout thenational territory.''   In telephone calls, reporters at Benin's state news agencyconfirmed that rioting broke out Monday night, but they refused togive details.   Demonstrators sacked several public buildings and burnedportraits of Kerekou, the French agency Agence France Pressereported.   Protesters chanted the name of Lt. Col. Francois Kouyami, said tobe one of the leaders of an attempted coup last year, said AFP.Kouyami escaped from prison in November.   Authorities have dispatched 300 extra troops to reinforce thegarrison in the capital, which is 20 miles east of Cotonou.   Porto Novo was the scene of several incidents earlier this monthwhen teachers, unpaid for several weeks, went on strike to demandtheir salaries. Unrest lasted a week, but the discontent hascontinued.   Kerekou has ruled since 1972, when he seized power in the tinyWest African nation's fifth coup since its independence from Francein 1960. The country used to be called Dahomey.</TEXT></DOC>